    "units" => 4, 
    "title" => "What is Beauty?", 
    "description" => "What or who decides whether something is beautiful or not? What purpose do beauty and art serve? Where do originality, genius, and inspiration come from? What do art and beauty have to do with freedom and human progress? We will examine primarily western European and North American approaches to beauty as presented in works of philosophy, literary theory, and theories of art and aesthetics, exploring key theoretical questions as they evolve among several intellectual arenas over many centuries. Also listed as Letters and Science C60T." 
  }, 
  { 
    "name" => "GERMAN.C76", 
    "number" => 76, 
    "units" => 4, 
    "title" => "Beauty and the Beholder: Approaching Art at the Berkeley Art Museum", 
    "description" => "This seminar-style course will take up a range of questions related to art works, aesthetic theory, the politics of art, and the relationship between artistic form and meaningful content by way of examinations of specific works at the UC Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive (BAM/PFA). Students will see how experts from several different disciplines approach works of art: What questions do scholars bring to an art work? What is a formal analysis vs. a critical interpretation of an art work? How do curators approach art? Are we supposed to 'learn from' an art work or 'experience' it or have some particular 'relationship' to it? Is art a matter of conveying feeling, a message, or an encounter with beauty? Also listed as Letters and Science C76." 
