  { 
    "name" => "S ASIAN.C127", 
    "number" => 127, 
    "units" => 4, 
    "title" => "Religion in Early India", 
    "description" => "Designed as a two-semester sequence, these courses are an introduction to the religions that have their origin on the Indian subcontinent--Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, Sikhism, and tribal religions--as well as those that originated in other regions such as Islam, Christianity, Judaism, and Zoroastrianism. Organizing this material chronologically rather than teaching it by separate religious traditions facilitates comparisons and promotes an understanding not only of the differences among these religions but also some of their commonalities in philosophy, theology, and praxis. Also listed as Religious Studies C161." 
  }, 
